I remember, in 2011, losing myself to the gym, to CrossFit, to a lifelong dream of being an athlete.
I remember blocking out all the noises and the negative self-talk, and running away from the negativity projected by people who couldn’t see the vision. Putting my head down and just grinding.
And now here we are, 12 years later, and I once again find myself closing in on the dark tunnel that has always led me directly to the most success. Starting to be more and more selective about those I invite on the adventure of a lifetime. Going dark, not answering texts, remembering not everyone is supposed to be part of the journey. No longer trying to convince anyone who can’t see the bigger picture without me having to vividly explain it. 
I can feel myself letting go of people, and holding on tighter to others, and just like the sea, I can feel the tide changing, pushing and pulling me into my next success story.
The universe, or god, or whatever you call the spirits who help guide us, always seem to have a special way of letting me know I’m lost. Kicking and screaming, sometimes for years, until I finally give in, to once again follow the path they’ve so beautifully created just for me ✨
—
Lean In. This is 2023. @endurelite 💙🤍✨

I hope that I don’t age gracefully.
I hope that I have eye wrinkles and cheek wrinkles from laughing and smiling too much, and sun spots from spending too much time outside.
I hope my eyes twinkle from the love I shared with the people I met.
I hope I need knee replacements because I kept hiking and climbing and exploring the world.
I hope my legs are covered in scars from crawling through bushes and falling off my bike and crashing in ocean waves.
I hope my hair is coarse and grey to show my wisdom and my forehead is furrowed to show focus and ambition.
I hope when I’m old, I look weathered and joyful and that my mind is filled with memories full of adventures and laughter and adrenaline.
—
I hope I’m one of the lucky ones, and that I get to live long enough to be old and wrinkly.

Hello Berlin,
I rode on planes and trains and boats, and in automobiles just to meet you this week.
I was told of your vibrant energy, your chaotic streets and a wall that made life impossible for those living on either side.
I was told that my soul might find peace amongst your chaos, and hope near your city’s heartbeat.
What I found when I finally arrived in your arms, is so much more than I ever imagined.
I found tears at the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe, and anger standing next to a 12 foot wall, but then, I found beauty in the graffitied underground world, and love on a border that not so long ago only knew hate.
You are magical, Berlin, in every possible way.
If you don’t mind, I’ll leave a suitcase here so that someday I will have to come back and visit you again.
I love you, I hope you love me too.
—
📷 - @takuma_oshima.jp

Most of my life is a battle between destiny and disaster, and I love it.

There are stages of triumph and success, and there are chapters of chaos and running away.

I'm caught in the transition right now, halfway between destiny and chaos, and I honestly love this part of the journey the most. When I don't know what I want, so I start to remove small pieces from my life, small pieces of me, and I slowly replace them with new adventures and dreams and goals and memories.

I keep core pieces, like my optimism, my silliness and my free spirit, but I replace other pieces, without my even realizing it, from new life experiences and traveling and loving and losing and learning.

I don't know where I'm headed, but l'm happy to be going there 💕
—

When I quiet my mind, and sit with just my own inner thoughts, I realize just how powerful and unique I am.
I notice how easily I adapt into new cultures, new places, new ways of thinking.
How level I can stay in a world that wants to spiral us out of control. Unable to be rattled by situations which later feel only like tests of character. Just how aware I am of my surroundings at all times which allows me to always feel comfortable, even when I don’t understand the languages being spoken all around me.
I am reminded how quickly I am able to become happy, anywhere, doing anything.
Travel has taught me a lot, but maybe the greatest lesson of all is that happiness is only found within oneself.
—
